ref: Jour: Nucl. Instrum. Methods in Physics Res., Sect.B, Vol.381, p.16 (2016)
title: Activation cross-sections of proton induced reactions on vanadium in the 37-65 MeV energy range

x4freetext: Activation cross-sections of proton induced reactions
on vanadium in the 37-65 MeV energy range

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nucl. Instrum. Methods in Physics Res., Sect.B, Vol.381, p.16 (2016)

x4codes.hlp: Catholic Univ. of Louvain, Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium

x4freetext: Targets were metallic V foils with natural isotopic
composition
The irradiation was
performed at one of the LLN cyclotrons with 65 MeV
protons for 1h at 35nA beam intensity.
The stack contained a 19 times repeated set of
10um Al, 116um In, 99.2um Al, 8.41um V, 99.2um Al,
26.2um Ho and 99.2um Al foils.
The beam energy and intensity parameters were further
adapted by taking into account the comparison of the
excitation function of the 27Al(p,x)22,24Na reactions,
re-measured over the whole energy domain studied, with
the recommended values in the updated version of
IAEA-TECDOC 1211.
Decay data were taken from NUDAT2.6 online database.

x4codes.shortRef: Rept: Nuclear Data Services (Doc. series of NDS), No.1211 (2001)

x4freetext: The uncertainty on the median energy in the
foils includes the cumulative effects of uncertainty of
incident beam energy, uncertainty of stopping power of
each foil due to thickness variation and  straggling
effects. Uncertainty of the primary incident beam was
+- 0.3MeV which increased up to +-1.3MeV in the last
foil of the stack.
The uncertainty on the cross section values
are estimated in the  standard way as the square root
of the quadratic summation of the independently
contributing parameters. Uncertainty of time parameters
is not included. Overall uncertainty were 12-14%.
surface density of target nuclei(5%),
incident charged particle flux (7%),
detector efficiency (10%)
nuclear decay and branching data(5%)
statistical and peak fitting (1-13%)
The experimental data were compared to the
results of the theoretical model codes TENDL.
The measured experimental data were compared to
those found in the literature.
Fitted excitation functions were used for
determination of integral physical yields.
